LeetCode 238. Product of Array Except Self
Approach 1: Brute Force
Idea

For every index i, iterate through the entire array and multiply all elements except nums[i].

Algorithm
For each index i:
Initialize product = 1.
Traverse the whole array.
If j != i, multiply product *= nums[j].
Store product in the answer array.
Time Complexity
Outer loop: O(n)
Inner loop: O(n)

Total: O(n²)

Space Complexity
O(1) (excluding output array)
Code
class Solution {
    public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] ans = new int[n];

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            int product = 1;

            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                if (i != j) {
                    product *= nums[j];
                }
            }

            ans[i] = product;
        }

        return ans;
    }
}

Approach 2: Using Division
Idea
Find the product of all elements.
For each index:
answer[i] = totalProduct / nums[i]
Example
nums = [1,2,3,4]

totalProduct = 24

answer[0] = 24 / 1 = 24
answer[1] = 24 / 2 = 12
answer[2] = 24 / 3 = 8
answer[3] = 24 / 4 = 6

Output = [24,12,8,6]
Time Complexity
O(n)
Space Complexity
O(1)
Code
class Solution {
    public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] ans = new int[n];

        int totalProduct = 1;

        for (int num : nums) {
            totalProduct *= num;
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            ans[i] = totalProduct / nums[i];
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
Limitation: This solution fails when the array contains zeros and the original problem explicitly disallows division.

Approach 3: Division + Zero Handling
Idea

Handle three cases:

More than one zero → all answers are 0.
Exactly one zero → only the zero index gets the product of non-zero elements.
No zeros → use product / nums[i].
Time Complexity
O(n)
Space Complexity
O(1)
Code
class Solution {
    public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] ans = new int[n];

        int zeroCount = 0;
        int product = 1;

        for (int num : nums) {
            if (num == 0) {
                zeroCount++;
            } else {
                product *= num;
            }
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            if (zeroCount > 1) {
                ans[i] = 0;
            }
            else if (zeroCount == 1) {

                if (nums[i] == 0) {
                    ans[i] = product;
                } else {
                    ans[i] = 0;
                }
            }
            else {
                ans[i] = product / nums[i];
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
Note:
Although this works correctly even with zeros, LeetCode 238 specifically asks you not to use division, so this is still not considered the intended optimal approach.

Approach 4: Prefix and Suffix Arrays
Idea

For every index:

answer[i] =
(product of all elements to the left)
×
(product of all elements to the right)

Maintain:

prefix[i] = product of elements before i.
suffix[i] = product of elements after i.

Then:

answer[i] = prefix[i] * suffix[i]
Example
nums   = [1,2,3,4]

prefix = [1,1,2,6]
suffix = [24,12,4,1]

answer =
1×24 = 24
1×12 = 12
2×4  = 8
6×1  = 6
Time Complexity
O(n)
Space Complexity
O(n)
Code
class Solution {
    public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {

        int n = nums.length;

        int[] prefix = new int[n];
        int[] suffix = new int[n];
        int[] ans = new int[n];

        prefix[0] = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            prefix[i] = prefix[i - 1] * nums[i - 1];
        }

        suffix[n - 1] = 1;
        for (int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            suffix[i] = suffix[i + 1] * nums[i + 1];
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            ans[i] = prefix[i] * suffix[i];
        }

        return ans;
    }
}

Approach 5: Optimal (Prefix Product + Running Suffix)
Idea

Instead of using separate prefix[] and suffix[] arrays:

Store prefix products directly in the answer array.
Traverse from right to left while maintaining a running suffix product.
Algorithm
First Pass (Left → Right)
ans[i] = product of all elements before i
Second Pass (Right → Left)

Maintain:

suffix = product of all elements after i

Then:

ans[i] = ans[i] * suffix
Dry Run
nums = [1,2,3,4]

After first pass:
ans = [1,1,2,6]

suffix = 1

i=3 → ans[3]=6×1=6, suffix=4
i=2 → ans[2]=2×4=8, suffix=12
i=1 → ans[1]=1×12=12, suffix=24
i=0 → ans[0]=1×24=24

Final Answer = [24,12,8,6]
Time Complexity
O(n)
Space Complexity
O(1) (excluding output array)

Code
class Solution {
    public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] ans = new int[n];

        // Store prefix products
        ans[0] = 1;

        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            ans[i] = ans[i - 1] * nums[i - 1];
        }

        // Multiply with suffix products
        int suffix = 1;

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            ans[i] *= suffix;
            suffix *= nums[i];
        }

        return ans;
    }
}

Summary Table
Approach	Idea	Time	Space	Accepted
1. Brute Force	Multiply all elements except current index	O(n²)	O(1)	✅
2. Using Division	totalProduct / nums[i]	O(n)	O(1)	❌ (fails with zeros, division not allowed)
3. Division + Zero Handling	Count zeros and handle separately	O(n)	O(1)	✅ (but uses division)
4. Prefix + Suffix Arrays	prefix[i] × suffix[i]	O(n)	O(n)	✅
5. Prefix + Running Suffix (Optimal)	Store prefix in answer array + one suffix variable	O(n)	O(1)	✅ (Best Solution)

Interview Flow
Brute Force
     ↓
Using Division
     ↓
Division + Zero Handling
     ↓
Prefix + Suffix Arrays
     ↓
Prefix + Running Suffix (Optimal, O(n) Time & O(1) Extra Space)

Key Formula:
answer[i] = (product of all elements to the left of i) × (product of all elements to the right of i)

The optimal solution simply computes these left and right products without using extra arrays.
